# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anna-apple
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anna-apple/adams-pearmain] '**Adams Pearmain**', also called '**Adam's Parmane**', is a cultivar of apple.
[src:anna-apple/adams-pearmain] It was introduced to the Horticultural Society of London in 1826 by Robert Adams, under the name '**Norfolk Pippin**'.
[src:anna-apple/adams-pearmain] The fruit is large, varying from two and a half inches to three inches high, and about the same in breadth at the widest part.
[src:anna-apple/adams-pearmain] It is pearmain-shaped, very even, and regularly formed.
[src:anna-apple/adams-pearmain] The skin is pale yellow tinged with green, and covered with delicate russet on the shaded side; but deep yellow tinged with red, and delicately streaked with livelier red on the side facing the sun.
[src:anna-apple/adams-pearmain] The flesh is reddish, crisp, juicy, rich, and sugary, with an agreeable and pleasantly perfumed flavor.
[src:anna-apple/adams-pearmain] This Cultivar is a sibling of Reinette de Hollande, a hybrid between Reinette Franche’ and ‘Reinette des Carmes.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The Agricultural Experiment Station established in 1921 developed into the Agricultural Research Organization (ARO), widely known as the Volcani Institute.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The Faculty of Agriculture of the Hebrew University of Jerusalem, Tel Aviv University, Bar Ilan University, Ben Gurion University of the Negev and the Weizmann Institute of Science also engage in agricultural research.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Farming has been practiced in the region which became Israel for 10,000 years.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] In the late 19th century Jewish and Palestinian Arab farmers expanded the acreage devoted to commercial and export crops.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The forerunners of agricultural research in Palestine were the teachers and instructors of the Mikveh Israel agricultural school, established in 1870.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The pioneers of many of the early farming settlements cultivated experimental plots supervised by an agronomist.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Arriving in the country with little or no previous agricultural experience, this kind of experimentation was vital for the development of such crops as grapes, citrus and almonds.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Arab agriculture revolved primarily around dry farming, with wheat, barley, chickpeas, sesame and olives predominating.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The few German Templer villages were based on relatively large farms of dry farming of wheat and barley.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] In 1906, Jewish agronomist Aaron Aaronsohn discovered wild emmer (*Triticum dicoccoides*), believed to be "the mother of the wheat.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] After the Balfour declaration by Great Britain in 1917 and the award of the mandate to Palestine by the League of Nations to Britain, the Jewish Agency established in 1921 the Agricultural Experiment Station.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Their mission was to conduct research leading to small farms with intensive agriculture, specializing in mixed farming of fruit trees, cattle, chicken, vegetables and cereals.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The research station, headed by Yitzhak Elazari Volcani and located in Rehovot, was the first scientific institute in Palestine.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] It had departments for crop sciences, fruit and citrus, soil and irrigation, entomology and plant pathology, post-harvest, food technology and farm economics.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The station had an extension department and results of its research were quickly passed on to the farmers.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Yields of grain under dryland conditions increased from 600 to 5000 kg per hectare; and breeding and selection of cattle increased milk production from 800–1500 kg to 5000 kg/cow/year (1950) {now more than 11.000 kg/cow/year- 2005}.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Research in storage of citrus fruit reduced spoilage during shipping to Europe due to fungal rots from 30% to 2-3%.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] In 1942 the Hebrew University in Jerusalem decided to establish the Institute for Agricultural Studies, which later developed into the Faculty of Agricultural, Food and Environmental Quality Sciences.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] In the beginning the faculty staff came mainly from the Agricultural Experiment Station and students worked on their theses in the laboratories of the Station.Michael Evenari (1904-1989, born as Walter Schwarz) was among the early pioneers.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The British government also established a small agricultural research department with several stations in both Arab and Jewish areas.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] After 1948, with the establishment of the State of Israel, the two research stations were merged into the Agricultural Research Station within the Ministry of Agriculture.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] However, the extension and advisory service, previously part of the research station, now became an independent branch within the Ministry.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The modern brand cherry tomato was developed by Israeli scientists in the 1970s.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] In 1960 an attempt was made to merge the Agricultural Research Station with the Faculty of Agriculture of the Hebrew University, to form the "National and University Institute of Agriculture." The idea was based on the US model of the Land Grant Colleges).
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] This attempt failed, mainly because the basic working conditions were not equalized before the merger.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Nevertheless, a close cooperation exists between the two institutions.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The senior researchers of the Agricultural Research Station serve on the teaching staff of the Faculty and students from the Faculty do their research for M.Sc. and Ph.D. theses at the Research Station.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] With the growth of the various disciplines in the Agricultural Research Station and the establishment of regional research stations, the organizational structure has changed over time.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The Agricultural Research Organization (ARO) was established in 1971, incorporating all agricultural research within the Ministry of Agriculture.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Within the ARO are six institutes, two commodity (Plant and Animal Sciences) and four discipline oriented institutes (Plant Protection, Soil, Water and Environmental Sciences, Technology & Storage of Agricultural Products and Agricultural Engineering).
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The ARO has two additional research centers – Gilat, in southern Israel and Neve Ya'ar in the north.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Within the six institutes the various scientific departments cover all agricultural disciplines except veterinary sciences.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] In addition to the Institutes the ARO maintains a computer unit, Genomics and Bio-informatics section, technology transfer (engaged in business related activities), international activities, youth activity units and a library.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The Veterinary Institute of the Veterinary Services of the Ministry of Agriculture is also located on the central campus of the ARO.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] These goals require development of new products and cultivars, improvement of food quality and safety, functional food, integrated pest management (IPM), precision agriculture and farming efficiency, with agricultural technologies friendly to the environment.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The fund of the Chief Scientist is open to scientists from all institutions – ARO, universities, regional research organizations, extension specialists and farmers.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] In addition to the Chief Scientist's fund the various commodity branches, as vegetables, flowers, fruits, dairy cattle etc. also allocate research funding of direct interest to them.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The Minister of Agriculture, upon recommendation of the Chief Scientist, appoints the committee members for research in each commodity branch.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] In general a third of the members come from the scientific community, a third from the extension service and a third are farmers.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The proposals submitted to the commodity branches also undergo the scientific evaluation process.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] A substantial source of funding, mainly for more basic research, comes from bi-national funds.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The leading one is The United States - Israel Binational Agricultural Research and Development Fund (BARD).
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] BARD is a competitive funding program for mutually beneficial, mission-oriented, strategic and applied research of agricultural problems, jointly conducted by American and Israeli scientists.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Since 1979, BARD has funded over 870 research projects, with awards of about $9.5 million annually for new research projects.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Most of these are of three years duration, the average award being $300,00.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Budgets are distributed about equally between the two countries.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Proposals are evaluated both in the US by the Agricultural Research Service (ARS) and in Israel by the Scientific Evaluation Committees (SEC), based on expert reviewers from different countries.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The recommendations from ARS and SEC are brought before a Technical Advisory Committee (TAC) for final recommendations to the Board of BARD.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The success of BARD led to the establishment of additional bi-national funds as the Joint Dutch-Israeli Agricultural Science and Technology Program, a bi-national Program with Queensland (Australia) and Canada.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The latter are all on a much lower funding level than BARD.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] In addition funding is also obtained from the EU, The US – Israel Bi-national Science Foundation (BSF) and others.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The Faculty of Agriculture, Food and Environmental Quality Sciences of the Hebrew University in Rehovot is a major partner in the conduct of agricultural research.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] In the Faculty, which includes Agricultural economics and management, a School of nutritional sciences and hotel, food and tourism management are about 90 tenured scientific staff.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The major scientific disciplines are: Agricultural Botany; Field Crops, Vegetables and Genetics; and Horticulture; Biochemistry, Food Science and Nutrition; Entomology and Plant pathology; Soil and water sciences; Animal sciences; Veterinary medicine and Agricultural economics and management.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Additional research is carried out at Bar-Ilan University, Tel Aviv University, the Weizmann Institute of Science, and Ben-Gurion University of the Negev, whose Jacob Blaustein Institute specializes in arid-zone agriculture.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The ARO and its forerunner, the Agricultural Research Station, have helped to turn Israel's “mixed farming” system into a highly industrialized enterprise focused on export to Europe.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Serious water shortages have led to the use of low quality and recycled water.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Some 44% of the water used for agriculture comes from recycled water without lowering quality of the produce.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Exports to Europe include fruits (citrus, avocado, grapes), vegetables (sweet peppers, tomatoes, potato, melons, sweet potato), ornamentals (cut flowers, potted plants, propagation material) and herbs.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] In 1997, agricultural export (fresh and processed) reached over $1.329 billion - approximately 6.4% of the country's total exports (Source: Central Bureau of Statistics).
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] This has necessitated an ongoing search for new products, niches in seasons and better storage technologies.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Major achievements included an increase in productivity of fruit, vegetable and field crops with a reduced input of chemical fertilizers and pesticides.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] Efficiency in dairy farming has increased milk production to one of the highest in the world: over 10,200 litre/cow/year.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] In 2010, Jonathan Gressel of the Weizmann Institute received the Israel Prize for agricultural research.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The prize committee chose Gressel, who is internationally known for his work in plant biotechnology, for breakthrough research in molecular structures that has major implications for the development of weed killers.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] The Israel Prize for Agriculture was previously awarded to about 10 different scientists mainly from the Agricultural Research Organization (previously the Agricultural Experiment Station) and the Faculty of Agriculture of the Hebrew University among them Prof.
[src:anna-apple/agricultural-research-in-israel] In 2012, Daniel Hillel received the World Food Prize for his pioneering work in micro-irrigation techniques.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Israel is home to two unique types of agricultural communities, the kibbutz and moshav, which developed as Jews immigrated to the land that became the State of Israel, and embarked on rural settlement.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] As of 2016, kibbutzim provided Israel with about 40% of its agricultural produce.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] The development of modern agriculture was closely tied to the Zionist movement and Jewish immigration to Ottoman Syria beginning in the late nineteenth century.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] By 1900, Jewish sector owned 3.8% of all cultivated lands in Palestine.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Jews mostly purchased land near the coast of the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Most Palestinian Arabs lived in the highlands and were subsistence farmers growing wheat and barley on rainfed land.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Both Jewish and Arab farmers initiated growing commercial and exportable crops such as citrus and vegetables in the late 19th century.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] The development of agriculture near the coast required drainage of swamps and eradication of malaria, but the land was "wonderfully rich and fertile".
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] A 1943 survey concluded that 435,700 ha (1,077,000 acres) of land in Ottoman Syria (21st century Israel, Judea, Sumaria and Gaza) was cultivated and that 24.9 percent of the cultivated land was owned by Jews.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Rain-fed cropland made up 91.7 percent of the total and 8.3 percent was irrigated.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] The Jewish residents of the new country of Israel gained farmland when 700,000 Arab Palestinians abandoned their homes, left the country or were forced off land inside the borders of Israel in the period leading up to and during the 1948 Arab–Israeli War.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] By 2001, 56.5 percent of the cropland in Israel was irrigated.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Since independence the production of export and commercial crops expanded while the acreage devoted to cultivation of wheat and barley declined.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Water shortage used to be a major problem.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Rain falls between September and April, with an uneven distribution across the country, from 700 mm (28 in) in the north to less than 20 mm (1 in) in the south.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Annual renewable water resources are about 160,000,000 cubic metres (5.6×10^9 cu ft), 75% of which is used for agriculture.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Most of Israel's freshwater sources have been consequently joined to the National Water Carrier of Israel; a network of pumping stations, reservoirs, canals and pipelines that transfers water from the north to the south.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] In recent years, Israel has invested heavily in seawater desalination.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] 80% of Israel’s fresh water is now made in 5 desalination plants.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Israel now pumps water into Lake Kinneret, the largest freshwater source in Israel.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] The share of agriculture in Israel’s GDP has steadily declined, falling from just under 6% in 1979 to 5.1% in 1985, and to about 2.5% in recent years.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] In 1995, there were 43,000 farm units with an average size of 13.5 hectares.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] 19.8% of these were smaller than 1 hectare, 75.7% were 1 to 9 hectares in size, 3.3% were between 10 and 49 hectares, 0.4% were between 50 and 190 hectares, and 0.8% were larger than 200 hectares.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Of the 380,000 hectares under cultivation in 1995, 20.8% was under permanent cultivation and 79.2% under rotating cultivation.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Farm units included 160,000 hectares used for activities other than cultivation.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Cultivation was based mainly in the northern coastal plains, the hills of the interior, and the upper Jordan Valley.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] In 2006, agricultural output fell by 0.6% following a 3.6% rise in 2005; inputs for 2007 rose by 1.2% excluding wages.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Between 2004 and 2006, vegetables accounted for around 35% of total agricultural output.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Flowers made up around 20%, field crops made up around 18%, fruits (other than citrus), around 15%, and citrus fruits around 10%.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] In 2006, 36.7% of agricultural output was for domestic consumption, 33.9% for domestic manufacturing, and 22% for direct export.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] In 2006, 33% of vegetables, 27% of flowers, 16% of field crops, 15.5% of fruits other than citrus, and 9% of citrus fruits were exported.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Israeli agricultural production rose 26% between 1999 and 2009, while the number of farmers dropped from 23,500 to 17,000.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Farmers have also grown more with less water, using 12% less water to grow 26% more produce.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] After the 2023 Hamas-led attack on Israel, many farmers in Israel faced large scale losses due to international workers being killed, kidnapped and/or leaving the country.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] While numerous volunteers initiatives were assembled by organizations such as Taglit-Birthright and HaShomer HaHadash, many farmers were unsure of the long term implications for their farms.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] On 15 November, the Agriculture and Finance Ministries, the Knesset Finance committee, and the Israeli Farmers Association agreed on a proposition to compensate farmers for their losses, although as of 24 November it had not been fully finalized.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Most of Israel's agriculture is based on cooperative principles that evolved in the early twentieth century.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Both communities provided a means not only to realise the dream of the pioneers to have rural communities based on social equality, co-operation and mutual aid but also to gain agricultural output in a productive means.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Today, between kibbutzim and moshavim, 76% of the country's fresh produce is output, as well as many processed food products.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Israeli farms relied mostly on Palestinian workers for additional labor up until the 1990s when, following the clashes of the First Intifada and the ensuing restriction on the movement of Palestinians from Gaza and the West Bank, Israel began to look at other areas for workers.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] A 2021 Knesset study relying on data compiled in 2020 found that about 75,200 people were employed in the agriculture sector with about 49% of them Israeli, 32% international and 19% Palestinians.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] By 2023, there were between 30,000 and 40,000 Thai workers working in the Israeli agriculture sector, and were governed by strict rules, such as being unable to raise families in the country and short contracts.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] After the 7 October 2023 attacks by Hamas, many Thai nationals returned to their home country, due to many being killed and held hostage in the attacks.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] This created a vacuum that caused large losses for the farmers, and a large influx of about 20,000 workers from Sri Lanka that were expected to arrive to work on the farms in December 2023.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] In November 2023, the Malawi government made an arrangement by Israeli companies to ferry Malawian farm workers to work farms in Israel.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Israel's agricultural sector's heavy reliance on less expensive foreign and migrant laborers has led to accusations of exploitation.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] To combat these violations, the Israeli High Court ruled in 1991 that all Israeli Labor Laws shall apply to the foreign workforce; although execution of the law remains difficult.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Problematic phenomena remain rampant and foreign worker continuously suffer from those such as black market laboring, sub-minimum wage, debt bondage, harsh, unsafe and inhumane work environment, human trafficking, false imprisonment, beatings, suicides and uninvestigated deaths.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Sexual assault of foreign agriculture workers is common, a 2021 report found that 100% of surveyed Thai agriculture workers had been sexually assaulted.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Due to the diversity of the land and climate across the country, Israel can grow a wide range of crops.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Field crops grown in the country include wheat, sorghum and corn.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] On 215,000 hectares of land, these sorts of crops are grown, 156,000 hectares of which are winter crops.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Fruit and vegetables grown include citrus, avocados, kiwifruit, guavas and mangos, grapes from orchards located on the Mediterranean coastal plain.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Tomatoes, cucumbers, peppers and zucchini are grown commonly throughout the country; melons are grown during winter months in the valleys.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Subtropical humid valleys in the country produce bananas and southern deserts grows dates, while in the northern hills apples, pears and cherries are grown.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Furthermore, grape vineyards are found across the country, as the country's wine industry has developed to become a world-player.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] In 1997, $107 million worth of cotton was grown in Israel with most of this sold in advance on the futures market.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] The crop is grown on 28,570 hectares of land, all of which is drip irrigated.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] 5.5 tons per hectare of raw cotton is averaged for the Acala crop; the Pima crop averages 5 tons per hectare, which are yields among the highest in the world.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] In 2010, cows in Israel were second only to Saudi Arabia in producing 10,035 kilograms (around 10,000 liters) per cow of milk in 2010, outperforming cows in the US (9,314 kg (20,534 lb) per cow), Japan (7,284), Korea (9,816), and Denmark (9,389).
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] A total of 1.6 billion liters of milk was produced by Israeli cows in 2023.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] All of Israel's milk consumption originates from dairy farms within the country with most herds consisting largely of Israel-Holsteins, a high-yielding, disease-resistant breed.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] In terms of poultry, which makes up two-thirds of meat consumption, 85% originate from moshavim.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] IAPV – Israeli acute paralysis virus – was first discovered here.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] After recent reports of severe mortality with symptoms similar to acute bee paralysis virus, Maori *et al.*, 2007 isolated IAPV and published an RNA sequence and several other molecular components.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] IAPV continues to be significant in apiculture here and has since been identified in colonies around the world.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] The Mediterranean Sea is a source of salt-water fishing; freshwater fishing occurs on Lake Kinneret (the Sea of Galilee).
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Pioneering technology is being used to breed fish in artificial lakes in the Negev desert.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Scientists of the Bengis Center for Desert Aquaculture at Ben-Gurion University of the Negev discovered that the brackish water under the desert can be used for agriculture, aquaculture and a combination of the two.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] This has led to the farming of fish, shrimp and crustaceans in the Negev.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Commercial fishing in the eastern Mediterranean has declined significantly due to depletion of fish reserves and the supply of fresh fish in Israel depends almost entirely on aquaculture.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Fish from the Sea of Galilee include silver carp, grass carp, grey mullet, St.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Peter's fish, rock bass, silver perch, and Asian seabass introduced from Australia.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Fish grown in cages submerged in the sea include gilthead seabream (called *denis* in Israel), European sea bass and a South American variety of meager.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Trout and salmon are raised in special canal-like ponds of running water of the Dan River, a tributary of the Jordan River.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Israel is a producer and exporter of citrus, including oranges, grapefruit, tangerines and a hybrid of a grapefruit and a pomelo, developed in Israel.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] More than forty types of fruit are grown in Israel.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] In addition to citrus, these include avocados, bananas, apples, olives, cherries, figs, plums, nectarines, grapes, dates, strawberries, prickly pear (*tzabbar*), persimmon, loquat and pomegranates.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Israel is the second leading producer of loquat after Japan.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] In 1973, two Israeli scientists, Haim Rabinowitch and Nachum Kedar, developed a variety of tomato with slower ripening than ordinary tomatoes in a hot climate.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Their research led to the development of the world's first long shelf-life commercial tomato varieties.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] This discovery transformed agricultural economics in Israel, promoting the export of the vegetables seeds and the move to high-tech farming.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] It also had a global impact, enabling large-scale production through the prevention of spoilage.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Previously, farmers were forced to discard 40 percent of their produce.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] The *Tomaccio* tomato was developed by Hishtil Nurseries, which conducted a 12-year breeding program using wild Peruvian tomato species to create a sweet snack tomato.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Avocados are a major "money spinner" for Israeli agriculture, with almost half (45 per cent) being sold abroad.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] In 2022, Israel ranked 9th among the countries in the world in the value of its flower exports which totaled almost $89 million.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] The flowers grown most commonly are *Chamelaucium* (waxflower), followed by roses, which are grown on 250 hectares (620 acres) of land.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] In addition to flowers favored in the West such as lilies, roses, and tulips, Israel exports desert varieties.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] It has become a major player in the global floral industry, especially as a supplier of traditional European flowers during the winter months.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Similar to floriculture around the world, Israel's flower cultivation relies heavily on introduced species.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Here these especially include *Ornithogalum dubium*, *Leucojum aestivum* and *Paeonia*.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Israel is a world leader in agricultural research and development, which has led to dramatic increases in the quantity and quality of the country's crops.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] The drive to increase yields and crop quality has led to the development of new seed and plant varieties, as well as to innovations such as a soil conditioner substance (vermiculite) which, when mixed with local soils, boosts crop yields, and drip irrigation.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] The Agritech Exhibition, held once every three years, is one of the leading international events of its kind to showcase Israel and international agriculture technologies.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] It traditionally attracts many Ministers of Agriculture, decision-makers, experts, practitioners and trainers in agriculture, and thousands of visitors.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] At the Agritech Exhibition in 2012 there were more than 35,000 visitors, and more than 250 exhibitors.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Organic produce makes up 1.5% of Israeli agricultural output, but it accounts for 13% of agricultural exports.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Israel has 7,000 hectares (70,000 dunams) of organic fields: Vegetable crops grown in open fields account for 65% of the land use, fruit orchards – 25%, hothouse vegetables – 6% and herbs – 4%.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Farm surpluses have been almost eradicated in the country, with farms having production and water quotas for each crop, which have stabilised prices.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Production quotas apply to milk, eggs, poultry and potatoes.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Israel's government also encourages a reduction in agricultural costs by trying to encourage specialised farming, and halting of production of crops for which no sufficiently profitable markets exist.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] The Ministry of Agriculture oversees the country's agricultural sector, including maintenance of standards of plant and animal health, agricultural planning, and research and marketing.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] A survey conducted across 2017–2018 made the first detection of *Xylella fastidiosa* in the country.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] This was found on almond in the Hula Valley, which is in the northeast.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Polymerase chain reaction (PCR) identified it as the *Xylella fastidiosa* subsp.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Agrotourism in Israel began gaining momentum towards the end of the 1980s as a response to declining agricultural incomes.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Many farmers sought alternative sources of income, leading to the development of rural and agricultural tourism.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] The Israel Ministry of Tourism began providing support in 1993, and in collaboration with the Jewish Agency, runs "Tourism Incubators" in peripheral regions.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] These incubators offer business advisory services, professional skills training, and business accompaniment for rural tourism operators.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Historical agricultural practices attract visitors to agritourism sites in Israel such as Ein Yael, Neot Kedumim, and Kfar Kedem.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] These locations showcase traditional methods like terraced farming and ancient irrigation.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Tourists can engage in activities such as grape stomping and olive pressing.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] The Wine Route and Olive Route in the Mate Yehuda and Yoav regions allow visitors to explore small wineries and ancient and modern oil presses.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] The Dagon Museum in Haifa displays the history of grain cultivation from ancient times to the present.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Binyamina, known for its citrus groves, and Kibbutz Ein Gedi near the Dead Sea, which demonstrates desert farming techniques, are also key agritourism sites.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] For insights into the development of modern agriculture, tourists can also visit the Dubrovin Farm museum and the Museum of Pioneer Settlement at Kibbutz Yifat.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] These sites depict the establishment of Israel's agricultural infrastructure in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] As of October 7, Kibbutz Alumim, located less than 4 kilometers (2.5 miles) from the Gaza border, housed 41 foreign workers, comprising 24 from Thailand and 17 agricultural students from Nepal.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] However, the attacks in October resulted in the destruction of chicken coops, greenhouses, and some irrigation equipment along the Gaza border.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] The Alumim Agricultural Company was the sole segment of the business that remained unaffected by the conflict.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] The primary revenue for Alumim is derived from agriculture, horticulture, and livestock.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] When some workers returned, the Israeli army initially prohibited the company’s agricultural operations.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Subsequently, limited access was granted.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] It was not planted in a timely manner and lacked the necessary care.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Certain crops, including carrots, sweet potatoes, cabbages, and others, could not be harvested.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] We had extensive greenhouses for peppers, but everything was ruined.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] We used to be the largest supplier of small sweet peppers.
[src:anna-apple/agriculture-in-israel] Currently, we operate a very small farm," stated the CEO of the company.
[src:anna-apple/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has large apples, weighing from 250 to 300 grams.
[src:anna-apple/aia-ilu] It is juicy, bittersweet, and has a weak aroma.
[src:anna-apple/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu is grown in nurseries, but is not widely propagated.
[src:anna-apple/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has low scab resistance and is resistant to powdery mildew.
[src:anna-apple/airlie-red-flesh] Oregon apple with bright pink flesh and speckled green skin.
[src:anna-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The **Airlie Red Flesh**, (also known as the **Hidden Rose** or the **Mountain Rose**), is a cultivar of domesticated apple.
[src:anna-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh tree will grow to a height of 4 meters (13 ft) to 5 meters (16 ft), and starts to fruit after about 4 years of growing.
[src:anna-apple/airlie-red-flesh] Airlie Red Flesh fruits are medium-sized, often small.
[src:anna-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The flavour of an Airlie Red Flesh apple has a balance of sweetness and tartness.
[src:anna-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple has dark red flesh and a crisp texture.
[src:anna-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple tends to ripen in late September.
[src:anna-apple/akane-apple] '**Akane'**, also known as '**Tokyo Rose'**, '**Tohoku No.3'** and '**Prime Red'**, is a Japanese cultivar of domesticated apple, that according to Orange Pippin is one of the best early season apples.
[src:anna-apple/akane-apple] 'Akane' was developed by the Morika Experimental Station of Japan sometime between 1900 and 1949, by crossing a Jonathan apple with a Worcester Pearmain, and was introduced to the United States in 1937, where it is very popular.
[src:anna-apple/akane-apple] 'Akane' is of moderately good disease resistance, best at warm climates but tolerates cold also.
[src:anna-apple/akane-apple] It flowers mid-late season, and should be harvested early-mid season.
[src:anna-apple/akane-apple] It is self-sterile and needs to be cross pollinated.
[src:anna-apple/akane-apple] It produces heavy crop of variable sized fruits, usually more to the smaller side, but good sized apples can be obtained by thinning.
[src:anna-apple/akane-apple] 'Akane' carries the fruit shape of the English 'Worcester Pearmain', and the unusually good balanced flavor of the 'Jonathan'.
[src:anna-apple/akane-apple] Shape ranges from flattened to heart-shaped.
[src:anna-apple/akane-apple] Fruits have a very good flavor, a blend of sweet and sharp, preferable for eating, keeps shape in cooking.
[src:anna-apple/akane-apple] Flesh color is white, with a yellow tinge.
[src:anna-apple/akane-apple] The apple is crisp, but not too dense; it is easy to eat.
[src:anna-apple/akane-apple] The fruit keeps fresh for about one week.
[src:anna-apple/alkmene-apple] '**Alkmene'** is a German cultivar of domesticated apple, also called '**Early Windsor'**.
[src:anna-apple/alkmene-apple] Two natural mutations (sports) of this cultivar that have red-skinned fruit have been selected: one called '**Red Alkmene'** was trademarked under the name of **Red Windsor**; the other is '**Ceeval'**.
[src:anna-apple/alkmene-apple] It was developed between 1900 and 1949, by the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute in Müncheberg, Germany, by crossing the two cultivars 'Cox's Orange Pippin' and 'Geheimrat Dr.
[src:anna-apple/alkmene-apple] Oldenburg' (frequently confused with the similar-sounding 'Duchess of Oldenburg').
[src:anna-apple/alkmene-apple] The result is an early harvest apple (early mid season), which is very attractive, with a honeyed flavor similar to Cox's but slightly sharper.
[src:anna-apple/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' flowers early mid season, with self-fertile blossoms, hence no cross pollination is needed.
[src:anna-apple/alkmene-apple] Fruit size is medium and variable, flesh color is yellowish or extremely yellow for an apple, skin has greenish-yellow background with orange-reddish flush and strong red strips.
[src:anna-apple/alkmene-apple] The 'Red Windsor' cultivar has a larger portion of red.
[src:anna-apple/alkmene-apple] It is resistant to apple scab and susceptible to blossom frost.
[src:anna-apple/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' was awarded the Award of Garden Merit by the Royal Horticultural Society in 1998.
[src:anna-apple/anna-apple] Anna was bred by Abba Stein at the Ein Shemer kibbutz in Israel, in order to achieve a Golden Delicious-like apple, that can be cultivated in nearly tropical areas.
[src:anna-apple/anna-apple] A regular apple needs between 500 – 1000 hours of chilling (aka chill units) in order to get in blossom, but Anna flourishes even with less than 300 hours, so it can be grown in warm climates.
[src:anna-apple/anna-apple] It is recommended for USDA hardiness zones 5–9, or rather 6–9.
[src:anna-apple/anna-apple] Anna was introduced in 1959, and is the most popular apple cultivar in Florida.
[src:anna-apple/anna-apple] Anna's skin color is very much like its Golden Delicious parentage, red flushed (by fifty percent) over green or greenish-yellow.
[src:anna-apple/anna-apple] It is excellent for fresh eating and keeps shape during cooking.
[src:anna-apple/anna-apple] It is self-sterile, and usually cultivated side by side with the Dorsett Golden cultivar or by Ein Shemer, all of which can be grown in warm climates and provide cross pollination for each other.
[src:anna-apple/anna-apple] Anna flowers and harvests at a very early season, gives a heavy crop, and keeps fresh 2–3 weeks.
